This paper discusses the development and evaluation of censorship resistance systems, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The focus is on link circumvention systems, which involve network infrastructure and communication protocols, making the paper relevant to the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the arms race between censors and circumvention systems, which involves the use of advanced technologies and techniques, making it relevant to the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The evaluation stack presented in the paper involves multiple layers, including network, transport, and application layers, making it relevant to the systems and control (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the challenges and mitigations for censorship resistance, which involves policy and legal considerations, making it relevant to the cryptography and security (cs.CY) sub-category.
